{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}} {{Spanish name|Meza|Flores}} {{Infobox criminal | name = Fausto Isidro Meza Flores | image = File:ElChapo-Isidro.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|6|19}} | residence = | death_date = | cause = | resting_place = | alias = ''El Chapo Isidro'' | allegiance = [[Beltrán Leyva Cartel]] | motive = | charge = [[Drug trafficking]], [[murder]] | conviction = | conviction_penalty = | conviction_status = | occupation = | spouse = }} '''Fausto Isidro Meza Flores''' (born June 19, 1982), commonly referred to by his criminal alias '''El Chapo Isidro''' ("Shorty Isidro"), is a Mexican drug lord and high-ranking leader of the [[Beltrán Leyva Cartel]], a drug trafficking organization. He is also the alleged leader of [[Los Mazatlecos]] and was right-hand man of the now deceased drug lords [[Héctor Beltrán Leyva|Héctor]] and [[Alfredo Beltrán Leyva]]. The FBI is offering a USD$5 million bounty.
==Criminal career==
===Early life and ascension=== Meza Flores (known in the criminal world as ''El Chapo Isidro'') was born on June 19, 1982.<ref name=family>{{cite web|title=MEZA FLORES: Drug Trafficking Organization |url=http://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/20130117_meza_flores.pdf |publisher=[[Office of Foreign Assets Control]] |accessdate=January 17, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DkDMVYxC?url=http://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/20130117_meza_flores.pdf |archivedate=January 17, 2013 |date=January 2013 |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref> He began his criminal career in the 1990s, at first working for the [[Juárez Cartel]] under the tutelage of the then-leader [[Amado Carrillo Fuentes]]. After the drug lord died of plastic surgery complications in 1997, Meza Flores deserted the organization along with several other drug traffickers and decided to join the forces of the [[Beltrán Leyva Cartel]]. As a member of the Beltrán Leyva brothers, he proved to be a "skilled hitman, capable of daring, cunning and bravado."<ref name=history1>{{cite news|title=Chapo Isidro: A History |url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/07/chapo-isidro-history.html |accessdate=January 18, 2013 |newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]] |date=July 9, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Dm1GetjV?url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/07/chapo-isidro-history.html |archivedate=January 18, 2013 |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref> When the leader [[Arturo Beltrán Leyva]] was gunned down and killed by the Mexican military in December 2009, many within the cartel deserted and left to form an independent criminal organization with [[Edgar Valdez Villarreal]], known as ''La Barbie''. Meza Flores, however, remained loyal to the Beltrán Leyva brothers and possibly forged an alliance with [[Vicente Carrillo Fuentes]].<ref name=history1/>
===Tubutama, Sonora shooting=== A fierce gunfight between members of the Sinaloa Cartel (with the backing of Gente Nueva) and the [[Beltrán Leyva Cartel]] (with the support of [[Los Zetas]] and Meza Flores' men) left about 30 dead in the town of [[Tubutama|Tubutama, Sonora]] in northern Mexico on July 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=El juego final de "Poncho Arce |url=http://www.riodoce.mx/content/view/11492/42/ |accessdate=December 14, 2012 |newspaper=[[Ríodoce]] |date=November 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Cu2CHznc?url=http://www.riodoce.mx/content/view/11492/42/ |archivedate=December 14, 2012 |deadurl=no |language=Spanish |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pedraza |first=Iván |title=Sicarios de los Beltrán Leyva y Zetas atacan a gente del Chapo en Sonora |url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf9ab0a9 |accessdate=December 14, 2012 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=July 2, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Cu2Hh4xF?url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/7c954b2a681dd8c89db2c26caf9ab0a9 |archivedate=December 14, 2012 |deadurl=yes |language=Spanish |df=mdy }}</ref> The drug gangs clashed just a few miles across the international border with the U.S. state of Arizona – an area notorious for being a smuggling route for narcotics and human trafficking.<ref>{{cite news|title=21 die in Mexican gang gunbattle near Arizona border |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/38050468/ns/world_news-americas/t/die-mexican-gang-gunbattle-near-arizona-border/#.UM0i13PjnDF |accessdate=December 16, 2012 |newspaper=[[MSNBC]] |date=July 1, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CwURER6q?url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/38050468/ns/world_news-americas/t/die-mexican-gang-gunbattle-near-arizona-border/ |archivedate=December 16, 2012 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy }}</ref> Reportedly, Meza Flores and a drug trafficker nicknamed ''El Gilo'' were the ones that carried out the surprise ambush attack on the gunmen of the Sinaloa Cartel.<ref name=history1/> Eleven late-model, bullet-ridden vehicles were found at the scene, along with dozens of assault rifles. Some of the vehicles had "X" painted on their windows, a method often used by the Mexican drug trafficking organizations to distinguish their vehicles from those of rival drug cartels during armed confrontations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico's drug war heats up near Arizona border |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/38093155/ns/world_news-americas/t/mexicos-drug-war-heats-near-arizona-border/#.UM0klnPjnDF |accessdate=December 16, 2012 |newspaper=[[MSNBC]] |date=July 5, 2010 |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CwUCDz3C?url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/38093155/ns/world_news-americas/t/mexicos-drug-war-heats-near-arizona-border/ |archivedate=December 16, 2012 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Beckhusen |first=Robert |title=Mexican hitman claims cartels bought guns from US Border Patrol |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-11/09/mexican-cartel-buy-guns-from-us-border-patrol |accessdate=December 16, 2012 |newspaper=[[Wired UK]] |date=November 9, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CwUJP28r?url=http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-11/09/mexican-cartel-buy-guns-from-us-border-patrol |archivedate=December 16, 2012 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy }}</ref>
===Los Mazatlecos era=== His gang, [[Los Mazatlecos]], is based in the region of [[Guasave, Sinaloa]], and is responsible for smuggling large quantities of methamphetamine, heroin, marijuana, and cocaine since 2000.<ref>{{cite news|last=Durán |first=Martín |title=Capturan a tres "mazatlecos" vinculados con matanzas de El Fuerte |url=http://noroeste.com.mx/publicaciones.php?id=805390 |accessdate=January 17, 2013 |newspaper=El Noroeste |date=August 22, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214043256/http://noroeste.com.mx/publicaciones.php?id=805390 |archivedate=December 14, 2013 |deadurl=no |language=Spanish |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ficha EU a rivales del cártel de Sinaloa: los Meza Flores |url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/640f14c3bba6f4cfe65887287be135d5 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=January 17, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DkDR0t2Z?url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/640f14c3bba6f4cfe65887287be135d5 |archivedate=January 17, 2013 |deadurl=no |language=Spanish |df=mdy }}</ref> He is one of the principal leaders of the [[Beltrán Leyva Cartel]] in the city of [[Mazatlán]] and in the mountainous areas of Sinaloa state. Since 2010, he is one of the leading rivals of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]]; the fight between the two drug trafficking groups has generated a wave of kidnappings and executions in Sinaloa.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castillo |first=Gustavo |title=Los Beltrán Leyva declaran la guerra al Chapo por el control de Sinaloa |url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2012/05/02/politica/015n1pol |accessdate=January 17, 2013 |newspaper=[[La Jornada]] |date=May 2, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DkFZAWMt?url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2012/05/02/politica/015n1pol |archivedate=January 17, 2013 |deadurl=no |language=Spanish |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Otero |first=Silvia |title=EU pone en lista de narcos a familia rival de El Chapo |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/896432.html |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)]] |date=January 17, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DkErIoh8?url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/896432.html |archivedate=January 17, 2013 |deadurl=no |language=Spanish |df=mdy }}</ref> Meza Flores was the right-hand man of [[Héctor Beltrán Leyva]] (now deceased) the top leader of the Beltrán Leyva Cartel; his area of operations is in Mazatlán, Guamúchil, Los Mochis, Choix and Los Cabos. On April 28, 2010, Meza Flores was nearly captured by Mexican law enforcement in the mountains of [[Choix, Sinaloa]]. However, the operation left two soldiers dead and twelve of his gunmen killed, including his right-hand man Omar Alfonso Rubio (alias "El Chonte"). On December 12, 2013, one of Meza Flores's top lieutenants, Ignacio "Nacho" González was arrested in Guasave, Sinaloa by the Mexican Army.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cae lugarteniente de "El Chapo Isidro" en Sinaloa |url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=360345 |accessdate=December 14, 2013 |newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]] |date=December 13, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214032620/http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=360345 |archivedate=December 14, 2013 |deadurl=no |language=Spanish |df=mdy }}</ref>
==Status== Meza Flores is a fugitive wanted by the United States government on drug trafficking charges. The FBI is offering a USD$5 million bounty.<ref>[https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/cei/fausto-isidro-meza-flores FBI Most Wanted: FAUSTO ISIDRO MEZA-FLORES]. FBI. Accessed: 19 November 2018.</ref> His last known residence was in the state of [[Nuevo León]], where he was reportedly seen with some of his family members at a youth basketball game in [[San Pedro Garza García]] on January 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cedillo |first=Juan |title=El rival de 'El Chapo' señalado por EU no tiene cargos en México |url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2013/01/21/el-rival-de-el-chapo-senalado-por-eu-no-tiene-cargos-en-mexico |accessdate=January 22, 2013 |newspaper=CNNMéxico |date=January 21, 2013 |agency=[[Turner Broadcasting System]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Dr5Z7GjO?url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2013/01/21/el-rival-de-el-chapo-senalado-por-eu-no-tiene-cargos-en-mexico |archivedate=January 22, 2013 |deadurl=no |language=Spanish |df=mdy }}</ref>
